    {
      "id": "pX1oFv6FQImF9ZBTNh84j",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 886.5468909370991,
      "y": 1051.0935788884801,
      "width": 1325.6788330078125,
      "height": 525,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b2f",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1041105599,
      "version": 251,
      "versionNonce": 1731388059,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1782143452432,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Architecture explanation:\nThe client starts a campaign and the Upload API creates campaign metadata and returns a presigned S3 upload URL. \n\nThe CSV lands in S3, and an object-created event or ingestion job (lambda) triggers workers to parse the file in chunks, validate rows, \nand create durable contacts and call tasks in PostgreSQL. \n\nThe eligibility scheduler reads due tasks from PostgreSQL and checks campaign status, local 8am-9pm calling windows, retry state, \nattempts below 3, and available campaign concurrency. \n\nEligible tasks are published to a dispatch SQS queue. \nDispatch workers poll the queue, claim the task, mark it dispatching, and call the telephony provider through a provider adapter.\n    \nThe provider sends asynchronous webhook events back to our webhook receiver. \nThe call state service validates and deduplicates those events, updates the call attempt state in PostgreSQL, \nstores transcript artifacts in S3, persists the structured outcome, releases campaign concurrency capacity, \nand publishes an outcome delivery message. \n\nCRM workers poll the outcome queue and send webhooks to the client CRM using a stable idempotency key, \nwith retry, backoff, delivery attempt logging, and DLQ/replay. \n\nMonitoring tracks ingestion progress, scheduler lag, active calls versus caps, provider errors, CRM delivery lag, and DLQ depth.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Architecture explanation:\nThe client starts a campaign and the Upload API creates campaign metadata and returns a presigned S3 upload URL. \n\nThe CSV lands in S3, and an object-created event or ingestion job (lambda) triggers workers to parse the file in chunks, validate rows, \nand create durable contacts and call tasks in PostgreSQL. \n\nThe eligibility scheduler reads due tasks from PostgreSQL and checks campaign status, local 8am-9pm calling windows, retry state, \nattempts below 3, and available campaign concurrency. \n\nEligible tasks are published to a dispatch SQS queue. \nDispatch workers poll the queue, claim the task, mark it dispatching, and call the telephony provider through a provider adapter.\n    \nThe provider sends asynchronous webhook events back to our webhook receiver. \nThe call state service validates and deduplicates those events, updates the call attempt state in PostgreSQL, \nstores transcript artifacts in S3, persists the structured outcome, releases campaign concurrency capacity, \nand publishes an outcome delivery message. \n\nCRM workers poll the outcome queue and send webhooks to the client CRM using a stable idempotency key, \nwith retry, backoff, delivery attempt logging, and DLQ/replay. \n\nMonitoring tracks ingestion progress, scheduler lag, active calls versus caps, provider errors, CRM delivery lag, and DLQ depth.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
